data: In his memorial of February 1608, Queirós refers to a memorial sent in December 1607. There are no known surviving copies of this memorial.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros, digo : que para descubrir la parte incognita del Sur ...
Queirós here describes his 1605-1606 expedition and lists some requirements for establishing a settlement.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiròs : despues q puse en pratica el descubrimiento de las tierras incognitas del Sur ...
In this memorial Queirós responds to five objections against establishing a settlement on Terra Australis.
Senor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros, que por mãdado de V. M. ...
In this memorial Queirós gives five reasons for establishing a settlement on Terra Australis.

Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros, con este son ocho los memoriales que a V.M. he presentado en razon de las poblacion q se deue hazer en las tierras que V.M. mandò que descubriesse en la parte Austral incognita ...
Queirós describes the lands he visited on his expeditions and the peoples he encountered.
Señor : ya he dicho a V. Magestad que de la parte del Sur, esta oculta la quarta parte del globo ...
Queirós here describes the other islands in the region.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : suplico a V.M. sea seruido ...

Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : de mostrar V.M. al mundo, quanto dessea, y procura la mas honra y gloria de Dios nuestro señor, en la poblacion que V.M. mãda q yo vaya a hazer, en las tierras q de la parte Austral por orden de V.M. descubri ...
This memorial was the first to be translated into other languages, after it was distributed beyond the Spanish court.

Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernádez de Quiros : de mostrar V.M. al mundo, quanto dessea, y procura la mas honra y gloria de Dios nuestro señor, en la poblacion que V.M. mãda q yo vaya a hazer, en las tierras q de la parte Austral por orden de V.M. descubri ...
Queirós explains how the 500,000 ducats required for the expedition will be spent, and describes the preparations for his earlier expedition.

Señor : el Capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : V.M. ordena y manda a su Consejo de Indias que me despachos a mi satisfacion para que el Virrey del Piru me de lo que fuere menester a la poblacion de las tierras Australes adonde V.M. se sirue mandarme ir.
In this memorial Queirós summarises the previous memorials and repeats his request for funding.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : cincuenta meses ha que estoy en esta Corte, suplicande a V.M. se sirua mandar me vaya a poblar las tierras que V.M. me mandò descubrir.
Queirós complains that he has now spent over four years at court waiting for permission and funding for his expedition.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : la parte incognita Austral es justamente quarta del Globo, sin saberse si es tierra, o si es agua, o que partes tiene de las dos ...
Queirós, having been told by the King to wait for a year, notes that this time has now elapsed and outlines his plans again.
Señor : capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros : V. Wagestad me mandò despachar dos vezes, la sequnda a mi satisfacion, juntamente esperar un año y son passados casi dos ...
In this memorial Queirós complains that he has now spent six years waiting at court. He outlines different ideas for funding the expedition and begs the King to consider them.
Señor : el capitan Pedro Fernandez de Quiros, a V.M. pido licencia para quexarme ...
Queirós continues to express his frustration at the King's failure to respond to his requests. This is the last known printed memorial.

table-0937-430.caption: Forts and trading posts
data: After having been granted to establish a factory in Pulicat in 1608, the local ruler allowed the Dutch to build a fort in 1613. This Fort Geldria remained the principal Dutch fort on the Coromandel Coast until 1690, when the headquarters changed to Negapatnam. In 1694, large portions of the artillery were shipped to Negapatnam, but after the latter's loss to the British in 1781, Fort Geldria was reinstated as the capital of the colony. The town was principal in the supply of cotton for the Dutch.

First established in 1612, but only in 1654 enlarged into a full factory. In 1749, the Sadras fort was completed. Together with Negapatnam, it was captured by the British in 1781, but contrary to Negapatnam, it was given back under the Treaty of Paris (1784). Sadras was renowned for its high quality cotton, and also supplied bricks for Batavia and Ceylon.
The local trading post was enlarged into a fort in 1758. Bheemunipatnam primarily traded in rice, and was fundamental for rice shipments to Ceylon.
An important textile trading post after the loss of Draksharama and Palakol (see below).
The Dutch East India Company settled in 1608 in an old house in Parangippettai, also known as Porto Novo. In 1680 extended into a full factory.
Temporarily abandoned in 1730. Trading post for textile, lamp oil, wood, roof tiles, and bricks.
Masulipatnam was the first Dutch factory on the Coromandel Coast of India. It was eventually abandoned in 1756.
Second Dutch factory on the Coromandel Coast. Abandoned in 1668.

Established in 1609. In 1647, the permission was given to build a fort here. The primary purpose of the settlement was to spy on the British, who had settled in the same town. Abandoned in favour of Parangippettai (Porto Novo) in 1758.

Important staple market for the Dutch East India Company. After having only a local tradesman to their service, the Dutch expanded their presence in Golkonda to a full factory in 1664. Due to local unrest, trade began to diminish in the late 17th century. The factory was eventually abandoned in 1733.
Abandoned in 1730 in favour of Jaggernaikpoeram.
Founded in 1608 on the ruins of an old Portuguese fort. Destroyed in 1625 by a local chief.
Established inland to have better control over the quality of the locally produced products. Destroyed on 13 October 1687 by locals.
